div.p:
We choose the square loss function to measure the error:

   \begin{equation*} l(y,\boldsymbol {x},\boldsymbol {\theta })=\frac {1}{2}(y-f(\boldsymbol {x},\boldsymbol {\theta }))^{2},\tag{4}\end{equation*}

      View Source

      \begin{equation*} l(y,\boldsymbol {x},\boldsymbol {\theta })=\frac {1}{2}(y-f(\boldsymbol {x},\boldsymbol {\theta }))^{2},\tag{4}\end{equation*}


and use the gradient descent method to minimize the loss:

   \begin{equation*} \boldsymbol {\theta }_{t+1} = \boldsymbol {\theta }_{t} - \eta \frac {\partial l(y_{t},\boldsymbol {x}_{t},\boldsymbol {\theta }_{t})}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }_{t}},\tag{5}\end{equation*}

      View Source

      \begin{equation*} \boldsymbol {\theta }_{t+1} = \boldsymbol {\theta }_{t} - \eta \frac {\partial l(y_{t},\boldsymbol {x}_{t},\boldsymbol {\theta }_{t})}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }_{t}},\tag{5}\end{equation*}


where

   $\eta $

is the learning rate.

The FIM is defined as follows
[11]
:

   \begin{equation*} \boldsymbol {F}(\boldsymbol {\theta }) = \left \langle{ \frac {\partial f(\boldsymbol {x}, \boldsymbol {\theta })}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }}\frac {\partial f(\boldsymbol {x}, \boldsymbol {\theta })}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }^{T}}}\right \rangle,\tag{6}\end{equation*}

      View Source

      \begin{equation*} \boldsymbol {F}(\boldsymbol {\theta }) = \left \langle{ \frac {\partial f(\boldsymbol {x}, \boldsymbol {\theta })}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }}\frac {\partial f(\boldsymbol {x}, \boldsymbol {\theta })}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }^{T}}}\right \rangle,\tag{6}\end{equation*}


where

   $\langle \cdot \rangle $

denotes the expectation with respect to the teacher distribution. The teacher distribution is given by:

   \begin{equation*} p_{0}(y,\boldsymbol {x})=q(\boldsymbol {x})\frac {1}{\sqrt {2\pi }\sigma _{0}}\exp \left ({-\frac {(y-f_{0}(\boldsymbol {x}))^{2} }{2\sigma _{0}^{2}}}\right).\tag{7}\end{equation*}

      View Source

      \begin{equation*} p_{0}(y,\boldsymbol {x})=q(\boldsymbol {x})\frac {1}{\sqrt {2\pi }\sigma _{0}}\exp \left ({-\frac {(y-f_{0}(\boldsymbol {x}))^{2} }{2\sigma _{0}^{2}}}\right).\tag{7}\end{equation*}

Then we introduce the types of singularities. As shown in
[11]
, besides of the overlap singularity and elimination singularity in the parameter space of unipolar-activation-function-based MLPs, there also exists opposite singularity for the bipolar-activation-function-based MLPs
(1)
, thus there are total three types of singularities:





         Opposite singularity:

            \begin{equation*} \mathcal {R}_{1} = \{\boldsymbol {\theta }|\boldsymbol {J}_{i}=-\boldsymbol {J}_{j}\},\tag{8}\end{equation*}

               View Source

               \begin{equation*} \mathcal {R}_{1} = \{\boldsymbol {\theta }|\boldsymbol {J}_{i}=-\boldsymbol {J}_{j}\},\tag{8}\end{equation*}








         Overlap singularity:

            \begin{equation*} \mathcal {R}_{2} = \{\boldsymbol {\theta }|\boldsymbol {J}_{i}=\boldsymbol {J}_{j}\},\tag{9}\end{equation*}

               View Source

               \begin{equation*} \mathcal {R}_{2} = \{\boldsymbol {\theta }|\boldsymbol {J}_{i}=\boldsymbol {J}_{j}\},\tag{9}\end{equation*}








         Elimination singularity:

            \begin{equation*} \mathcal {R}_{3} = \{\boldsymbol {\theta }|w_{i}=0\}.\tag{10}\end{equation*}

               View Source

               \begin{equation*} \mathcal {R}_{3} = \{\boldsymbol {\theta }|w_{i}=0\}.\tag{10}\end{equation*}

The analytical form of FIM

   $\boldsymbol {F}(\boldsymbol {\theta })$

is given by:

   \begin{align*} \boldsymbol {F}(\boldsymbol {\theta })=\left \langle{ \frac {\partial f(\boldsymbol {x}, \boldsymbol {\theta })}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }}\frac {\partial f(\boldsymbol {x}, \boldsymbol {\theta })}{\partial \boldsymbol {\theta }^{T}}}\right \rangle =\begin{bmatrix} \boldsymbol {F}_{1}(\boldsymbol {\theta }) &\quad \boldsymbol {F}_{2}(\boldsymbol {\theta })\\ \boldsymbol {F}_{3}(\boldsymbol {\theta }) &\quad \boldsymbol {F}_{4}(\boldsymbol {\theta }) \end{bmatrix},\end{align*}

      View Source

